WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Thank you very much, Hadley. Today I'm going to talk about free and open source software

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.680
for data science. The lens I'm going to use to talk about it is kind of the how and why

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:27.879
of RStudio. A little bit about how the company got started and where our mission of creating

00:00:27.879 --> 00:00:32.840
free and open source software sort of derives from. But then I want to get into the ways

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:38.639
that tools, both open source and proprietary, for scientific and technical computing are

00:00:38.639 --> 00:00:44.000
developed. How are they financially supported? How are they sustained? How can you come to

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:51.000
trust them? And get into a little bit about the nature of corporations as stewards of

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:57.200
this sort of software. And I'll ask the question, are corporations kind of inherently sketchy

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:03.720
as stewards of this sort of software? Spoiler, they are. So then I want to talk a little

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:11.120
bit about what we can do about that. So I'll start by a little background about how the

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.959
company got started so you can get a flavor for kind of where I was coming from starting

00:01:14.959 --> 00:01:21.720
the company. The seeds of the company go all the way back to 1983. How many people here

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:26.599
have heard of Bill James? People have heard of Bill James? Okay. So Bill James was a math

00:01:26.599 --> 00:01:34.800
teacher in Kansas City. And back in 1983, I was an avid follower of baseball. And I

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:41.800
absorbed all of the, you know, analysis about baseball from writers and sportscasters and

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:47.160
players and coaches and experts. And I came to believe a lot of the things I was hearing

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:54.599
about kind of how baseball teams win games, how you assess the value of players and strategies.

00:01:54.599 --> 00:01:59.400
So what Bill James did, interestingly, you can see back in 1977, his first baseball abstract

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:04.879
was this little pamphlet. He went from that pamphlet over ten years to a New York Times

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:12.559
bestselling book where he used data, empirical data analysis, to systematically debunk many

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:18.440
of the assumptions that people had about kind of how baseball works. And for me, as a 14-year-old,

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:23.720
that was really striking that all these people who were, you know, who had spent their lives

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:27.160
in the game of baseball, who had developed kind of conclusions and intuitions about how

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:33.520
it worked, that all of that could be debunked by systematically using data. It was shocking

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:39.440
to me. And that stuck with me. When I went to college, I didn't go to college for baseball

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:45.000
studies. I went to college for political science. And when you talk about political science,

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.240
you get into public policy. And public policy decisions are made that affect the well-being

00:02:50.279 --> 00:02:55.160
of many, many hundreds of millions of people. And so the same thing occurred to me that

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:59.399
we've got lots of experts and we've got lots of people who've been absorbed in different

00:02:59.399 --> 00:03:05.440
fields and observing phenomena for years making these decisions and possibly, probably as

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:11.199
it turned out, not actually using data to inform those decisions. And as I've become

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:14.960
part of the R community, I've realized that the same phenomena repeats in fields like

00:03:15.039 --> 00:03:21.559
medicine and business, that people are making highly consequential decisions and they're

00:03:21.559 --> 00:03:26.679
not availing themselves of the tools they have to really understand how the world works.

00:03:26.679 --> 00:03:33.679
So this then kind of, to me, through college, struck me as kind of the fundamental problem

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:39.839
to solve. And it seemed to me that software was an important part of the answer. This

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:44.880
is some of the software that I used in college and graduate school. And say what you might

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:50.279
know about some of the software, I had the experience of software providing leverage.

00:03:50.279 --> 00:03:55.919
So my mind and what I could absorb was amplified by the fact that I could use the software

00:03:55.919 --> 00:03:58.839
to better understand things.

00:03:58.839 --> 00:04:05.119
So from there, I went to graduate school at the University of Wisconsin-Madison studying

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:09.119
political science. And this is going to be an aside that this group, I think, will find

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:13.199
interesting. It's not really in the main thread of the talk. But I worked on a study there

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:18.160
that was studying the effectiveness of vouchers and public school performance in Milwaukee.

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:21.760
Milwaukee was one of the first, if not the first, cities to implement a school voucher

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:27.399
program. And there was a study going on at Madison that was going to assess how effective

00:04:27.399 --> 00:04:30.559
school vouchers were. And I worked on that study.

00:04:30.559 --> 00:04:36.079
So at the same time, there was a group at Harvard that was very convinced that the conclusions

00:04:36.079 --> 00:04:39.839
that would be drawn by the folks at Madison were going to be wrong. So they were very

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:44.959
keen to reproduce and criticize the results of the study.

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:50.959
So they asked for the data. They said, can we please have the data so we can do our own

00:04:50.959 --> 00:04:56.440
analysis? So we had the data in Paradox databases that were machine-readable, super easy to

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:01.839
send to them. But what we did instead, true story, was we printed out all the data and

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:06.640
shipped them crates of paper so that they could reenter the data on their own.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:13.640
So that's kind of where we were in reproducibility and academia back then. So that's a true story.

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:21.880
So when I got to Madison, I was really excited about data analysis and computation. And I

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:27.600
was kind of like, could I kind of specialize in software for data analysis? And unfortunately,

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:31.320
in political science at that time, software was definitely not something you could specialize

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:36.000
in. And at Madison, even data analysis was kind of barely something you could specialize

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:36.200
in.

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:40.440
So I was kind of in the wrong place. So while I was trying to, when I was supposed to be

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:44.920
doing my graduate school work, I was teaching myself how to program in C++ and teaching

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:50.200
myself how to program in the Mac. And that inevitably led shortly to me dropping out

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:54.160
of the program and saying, I want to be a software engineer.

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:58.440
And what I alluded to just a little bit before, what fascinated me so much about being a software

00:05:58.799 --> 00:06:05.079
engineer is summed up well by this quote from Steve Jobs, where he says, what a computer

00:06:05.079 --> 00:06:08.839
is to me, it's the most remarkable tool that we've ever come up with. It's the equivalent

00:06:08.839 --> 00:06:14.399
of a bicycle for our minds. And the other thing he cites in that when he recounted that

00:06:14.399 --> 00:06:19.160
quote was there was a scientific American study that looked at the sort of efficiency

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:26.160
of different modalities of motion, sort of the cost of transport, calories per gram per

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:28.880
kilometer as it relates to body weight.

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:34.000
So they looked at, you know, organisms, salmon were super efficient, horses were super efficient.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.160
They looked at different modalities of human transportation and they found that a person

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:44.279
on a bicycle was by far the most efficient. And that's, I think, what computers are and

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:45.279
what software is.

00:06:45.279 --> 00:06:50.880
So that became my fascination and I decided I want to become a software engineer and I

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:56.519
wanted to build software tools. So I did that for quite a number of years. I built

00:06:56.519 --> 00:07:02.119
programming tools, I built research tools, I built some writing tools. And the software

00:07:02.119 --> 00:07:07.640
I worked on was, had a couple of characteristics. One was it was proprietary software. Two was

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:13.480
I was working in startup companies. And proprietary software worked on in startup companies is

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:19.920
almost, it has sort of the seeds of its demise built in from the beginning. Because startup

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:24.679
companies are built to be sold and usually when they're sold they're in some form or

00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:31.200
fashion kind of destroyed or warped. And the proprietary software is often very bound up

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:34.239
in the fortunes and fate of the companies that sponsor its development.

00:07:34.239 --> 00:07:39.200
So I really enjoyed working on software tools but I found that proprietary software in startups

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:43.880
was not something I wanted to do anymore after that. So I was sort of searching for what

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:50.839
I'd like to do next. And I came to the conclusion that one of the things I wanted was I wanted

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:55.920
to build tools that were durable that could outlast a given company. And I wanted to build

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:00.440
tools that were accessible to everyone. That anyone could use irrespective of cost. And

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:04.480
that led me to the idea of working on open source software. So I knew I wanted to work

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:10.000
on open source software. I knew that I didn't want to do software startups. And at that

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:15.519
time I found out about R, which kind of took me back to the work that I had done in data

00:08:15.519 --> 00:08:20.000
analysis as an undergrad in graduate school. And it took me not very, I don't know how

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.600
long it took me, it was definitely less than 24 hours to conclude this is what I want to

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:27.279
work on. At the time I felt like maybe for the next 10 years, now I feel like for the

00:08:27.279 --> 00:08:34.280
rest of my career. So I was very lucky to discover R. And it also felt to me like I

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:39.280
could offer something to the community. Because I had worked on kind of programming tools

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:49.280
and tools to make people more productive with complex software. So I also didn't want to

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:53.280
do a startup. And I thought, well, you know, this is fine. Because I think one or two people

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:56.280
could actually make a significant contribution. We wouldn't need to have a startup. We could

00:08:56.280 --> 00:09:00.280
just make a contribution. And so that's when I started working on the RStudio IDE. And

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:06.280
I worked on it initially by myself. And then Joe Chang, who I had worked with a couple

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:10.280
of previous companies, joined me a few months later. And together we set out to build the

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:14.280
RStudio IDE. And the general mission was to try to make a contribution to open source

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:22.280
software for statistical computing. So I want to now say, you know, why is free and open

00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:27.280
source software for science and data science so important? At the time I was focused on

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:35.280
this idea of durability and accessibility. But as I've joined the R community, I've come

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:40.280
to realize there's lots of other good reasons to prefer open source software for data science.

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:46.280
So I want to get into a little bit of that. And I first want to make a distinction between

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:53.280
different senses of the word free. There's for free, gratis. And there's with little

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:58.280
or no restriction, libre. And both are relevant, obviously, with open source software. Famously

00:09:58.280 --> 00:10:03.280
Richard Stallman summarized the difference and the nature of libre as think free as in

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:09.280
free speech, not free beer. We sometimes with free software focus too much on the fact that

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:15.280
the software has no cost. But the most important thing is that it comes without restrictions.

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:21.280
And they actually the new summarizes kind of the four essential freedoms of free and

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:26.280
open source software. And they mostly have to do with being able to do with the program

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:31.280
what you wish, including inspect it, modify it, create your own derivative works from

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:36.280
it. And the fact that you are not dependent upon the original purveyor of the software

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:42.280
to continue using or evolving the software. So that's actually for science especially

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:46.280
more important. The fact that it comes without cost is important. That's actually even more

00:10:46.280 --> 00:10:53.280
important. So what are some of the reasons why we want to prefer free and open source

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:58.280
software? Well, this I don't need to speak at any length about this with this group.

00:10:58.280 --> 00:11:02.280
But it's worth reflecting on the fact that if I use proprietary software to do science

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:07.280
or data science and someone else wants to reproduce my results, at the best that person

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:12.280
needs to buy a license for the software that I used. But at worst, and this often happens,

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:17.280
I can't even reproduce my own work in the future because maybe the vendor who created

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:21.280
the software has gone out of business or they've made older versions of their products inaccessible.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:27.280
So long-term reproducibility is really only assured by using free and open source software.

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:32.280
I want to point out briefly just how important the R community has been in this movement

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:38.280
toward reproducibility. There was an article written in Nature in 2012 sort of making this

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:44.280
case, and at the time they cited there were two systems known to enable the packaging

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:49.280
of code, data, and text at the time. One of those two was Sweve, which the R community

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:54.280
actually came up with in 2002. So we've been at this for 18 years, certainly longer than

00:11:54.280 --> 00:12:03.280
any other programming language community. There's another consideration, which is resiliency.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:09.280
As I said before, software products and companies come and go. We don't want our research, our

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:14.280
ability to reproduce the research, tied to the fate of a specific product or vendor.

00:12:14.280 --> 00:12:20.280
Now, a variation on this theme is that software doesn't come and go. It actually stays and

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:25.280
becomes really, really important to customers, and then the vendor decides, oh, this is an

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:30.280
opportunity for us to dramatically raise prices and extract more value from our customers.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:36.280
So notably, the four essential freedoms that I talked about ensure that this cannot happen

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:40.280
with free software. There's a great example of this from the database world, where MySQL,

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:46.280
which is a GPL open source database, was acquired by Sun, and then subsequently Sun was acquired

00:12:46.280 --> 00:12:52.280
by Oracle. So Oracle, a proprietary database vendor, now owned all the copyrights to MySQL,

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:58.280
and they were gearing up to try to do all kinds of things to try to exploit that position.

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:04.280
And even though Oracle actually owned all the copyrights for MySQL, the community took

00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:09.280
the code from MySQL, forked it, and created another product called MariaDB and continued

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:13.280
on with development. So only the fact that that software was free and open source kind

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:18.280
of ultimately protected the community from a vendor that was going to be abusive.

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:23.280
And we can think in the R community, RStudio and many other vendors have provided offerings

00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:30.280
around R, and the commitments of vendors can vary over time. Companies can get acquired,

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:37.280
they can shift strategies. If, as a user, your primary investment is an open source

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:42.280
R code that will run irrespective of any vendor's products, then you're protected from that.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:45.280
You have that resiliency.

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:51.280
There's another piece, which is participation. I think maybe 10 or 15 years ago, many people

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:56.280
might have believed, well, a proprietary software vendor can kind of enumerate and

00:13:56.280 --> 00:14:01.280
account for all the methods that are important in a field and then provide that. Or a lot

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:06.280
of people believed that. I think now the explosion of innovation in statistical methodology,

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:13.280
nobody believes that, that a single vendor could be the filter who decides what methods

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:19.280
are supported and available and easy to use. So the fact that we have an open source ecosystem

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:25.280
around R enables what you've seen with CRAN, where there's this huge long tail of innovation.

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:29.280
There can be many, many different approaches to analysis, there can be innovation in methods,

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:33.280
and it's all supported by the software. So participation is another fundamentally important

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:34.280
thing.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:41.280
And finally, what I talked about at the beginning, accessibility. And data literacy is becoming

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:46.280
it's fundamentally important for organizations, it's also fundamentally important for individuals.

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:52.280
And open source software allows everyone to participate and use these tools, again,

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:56.280
without regard for cost.

00:14:56.280 --> 00:15:02.280
So let's talk then a little more generally about how these tools for, you know, not just

00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:06.280
data science, but tools for scientific and technical computing get built. Both proprietary

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:11.280
tools and open source tools. How they're built, how they're funded, what the underlying kind

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:15.280
of structural incentives are.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:21.280
Looking at the history of scientific and technical computing companies, these are leaders, if

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:26.280
you don't recognize them by company name, you certainly recognize their products, SAS,

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:32.280
MATLAB, Mathematica. And they actually have some significant shared characteristics. All

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:36.280
of them started in academia by one or two people, and over the first few years of the

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:41.280
project, it was only one or two people. And then eventually they sort of organically spread

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:44.280
within academia and then grew into becoming companies.

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:51.280
All of these companies, I would say, if you look at their about page or read the writings

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:56.280
of their founders or talks by their founders, they identify their principal mission is to

00:15:56.280 --> 00:16:01.280
support research and science, not profit. And consequently, these are all private companies.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:06.280
None of these are publicly traded. They're all closely held by the original group that

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:12.280
founded them. And of course, notably, they all make proprietary software, not open source

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:13.280
software.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:19.280
So, what's problematic about this kind of mirrors what I said about what's good about

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:25.280
open source software. We have reproducibility problems, accessibility problems, centralizing

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:32.280
decisions about what methods are supported. And there's also that risk of companies that

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:37.280
want to perpetuate themselves, be incentivized to kind of hold their customers hostage.

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:42.280
So, those are some problems. One really good thing about these companies, though, is that

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:46.280
they actually have an economic engine that they can use to fund development. And without

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:50.280
some kind of an economic engine, oftentimes sufficient progress isn't made. The tools

00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:54.280
actually don't reach the bar where people can use them to solve all the problems.

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:58.280
So, they have some significant drawbacks, but they have that benefit of having this

00:16:58.280 --> 00:16:59.280
economic engine.

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:04.280
So, now let's consider open source tools for scientific and technical computing. The ones

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:10.280
that the people here are probably most hands-on familiar with are the ones, the R and Python

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:15.280
data science ecosystems. But there have been lots of tools before that, notably SageMath

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:20.280
and GNU Octave. And these all have roots quite similar to the proprietary software

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:25.280
vendors. They started in academia. They grew very slowly and organically at the beginning.

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:31.280
And the founders of these projects also were concerned principally with supporting research

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:36.280
and science. And they wanted to protect the software. Their means of protecting it was

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:41.280
to make it open source. Because at the time a lot of these projects emerged, the idea

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:46.280
of open source had gained more currency. The viability of open source had more currency.

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:53.280
Linux had achieved some success. So, this is the approach that these projects have taken.

00:17:53.280 --> 00:18:00.280
And so, what's problematic here is do these projects have enough funding to sustain momentum

00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:07.280
and get where users want them to be? And honestly, over half of software engineering is solving

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:14.280
boring problems. And sometimes you just need to have a size of team and a commitment of

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:20.280
a team to go and solve those difficult and boring problems. So, you know, getting enough

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:24.280
resources is the same. These projects can be a challenge. And there's also an issue

00:18:24.280 --> 00:18:29.280
of sort of project organization. Are these projects cohesive enough to deliver the software

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:36.280
that users need? And then significantly, are organizations who are making decisions about

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:40.280
taking big long-term dependencies on software projects, are they comfortable adopting the

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:44.280
software without visibility into the long-term health of the project? Will the project be

00:18:44.280 --> 00:18:51.280
around? So, there's different ways that people have come up with to fund open source development.

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:55.280
There's grants, and Jupyter has actually done quite a bit with grants. There's probably

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:59.280
a natural limit to how much funding you can get from grants, but Jupyter's done quite

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:04.280
well with that. Open source software can be funded by companies that have an interest

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:08.280
in the software, and Linux is the best success story here, where lots of really large companies

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:14.280
that have an interest in having a free, robust, free Unix operating system all contributed

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:19.280
to it. And that's the initial model for Ursa Labs working on Apache Aero, where there's

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:23.280
a bunch of companies, including our studio, that have invested in building the software

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:28.280
because we think it's going to benefit our users. There's also the traditional method

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:35.280
of venture capital, but if you look at those companies I talked about, MathWorks, SAS,

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:39.280
Wolfram, they've been around, the evolution of their products and the adoption of their

00:19:39.280 --> 00:19:45.280
products took like 30 or 40 years. They've been around for a long time. The venture capital

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:50.280
model is much, much shorter, so I don't think it fits particularly well with building open

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:57.280
source tools for science. So, the question is, do any of these models actually work?

00:19:57.280 --> 00:20:03.280
And this question was asked rather, or answered rather poignantly, or pointedly, by a gentleman

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:08.280
from Wolfram, because apparently Wolfram gets asked all the time, why isn't Mathematica

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:15.280
open source? And so, he wrote a blog post, 12 Reasons Why It's Not Open Source. And I'm

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:20.280
not going to read these reasons out loud to you. If you take a quick scan of them, I think

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:27.280
you can get a sense for what the reasons are. And I would say, generally, I agree with

00:20:27.280 --> 00:20:34.280
this analysis to the extent that I do believe that you have to assemble a group that works

00:20:34.280 --> 00:20:38.280
together to achieve a set of shared goals over a sustained period of time. You have

00:20:38.280 --> 00:20:42.280
to have strong technical leadership to solve hard problems, and you do need a financial

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:46.280
engine that can compensate talented people to work on these problems. That's kind of

00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:52.280
the main gist of his case. I agree that those things are required, but I actually think

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:57.280
it's possible to do it with open source software. And I think that the kind of history of our

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:04.280
studio demonstrates that. So, if you look a little bit at the history of the company,

00:21:04.280 --> 00:21:10.280
2008, late 2008, I believe, when we started, it was, as I said before, just one or two

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:17.280
or three people working on open source software. And then about seven years ago, we decided

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:23.280
that we thought we could do a lot more with just having three people working on open source

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:27.280
software was fine, but we thought there was potential to do a lot more. And so we made

00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:32.280
a decision at that time to build a company around the open source work we had done with

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:38.280
the notion that we could fund lots more open source development if we had a company producing

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:42.280
revenue to fund the development. So we did that, and you can see over the last seven

00:21:42.280 --> 00:21:46.280
years or so, we've produced a huge amount of open source software. We have, I think,

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:52.280
over 250 open source projects that we are active developers on. And we have this set

00:21:52.280 --> 00:21:57.280
of commercial products that we sell, and we've grown from that original one or two or three,

00:21:57.280 --> 00:22:05.280
six people, to now over 150 people. Our company is profitable, so we're able to take the revenue

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:10.280
from our commercial products and feed it back into open source development and then

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:14.280
continue as the company grows to grow that commitment over time. So I think we've figured

00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:19.280
out a model by which we can still produce open source software, but do it in this kind

00:22:19.280 --> 00:22:26.280
of sustainable, well-funded way. We sometimes refer to this as a virtuous cycle where we

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:30.280
create open source software, and lots and lots of people, because it's accessible, lots

00:22:30.280 --> 00:22:35.280
and lots of people use it. And when lots and lots of people use software, what happens

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:40.280
is large organizations start to adopt the software. And larger organizations typically

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:44.280
have deployment and management and scalability requirements that are different than individuals

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:49.280
or small groups, and that creates an opportunity for us to build products, to solve those problems,

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:54.280
which then gives us revenue to invest back in open source tools. Now you'll notice here,

00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:59.280
it's pretty subtle on this slide, there's a line between these things. And you might

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:04.280
ask the question, well, where's that line, and where's the assurance that a company like

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:09.280
RStudio, as I said, corporations are inherently sketchy, isn't going to move that line at

00:23:09.280 --> 00:23:14.280
some point. Let me give you the operative principle for us that's behind that line.

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:19.280
The operative principle has to do with preserving those four freedoms. So the core libraries,

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:26.280
packages, protocols, file formats, even productivity tools like RStudio IDE need to be open source

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:33.280
so that users who adopt the software experience the benefits of those four freedoms, and essentially

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:38.280
the work is not locked in to the products of a given software vendor. The tools that

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:44.280
we create to facilitate adoption of R in large, complex environments, those tools are commercial.

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:50.280
Those are tools that, candidly, if we're not providing good value to customers, they can

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:55.280
continue using R, continue using the Tidyverse, R Markdown, Shiny, everything without those

00:23:55.280 --> 00:24:00.280
tools. So for us, we have to continue to offer a good value proposition, our customers can

00:24:00.280 --> 00:24:05.280
walk away. And that's because the core software preserves the four freedoms. So that's kind

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:10.280
of where we draw the line and how we think about open source versus commercial.

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:16.280
So I think we've managed to create a new kind of scientific and technical computing company.

00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:23.280
I think we have those attributes that the gentleman from Wolfram cited, which is that

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:28.280
we have a financial engine that we can work on this in a sustained way for many years

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:34.280
and apply adequate resources. We also, like those companies, think it's critical that

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:40.280
we remain independent to pursue our mission. But we've managed to do this in a way where

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:46.280
the core software is open source and we don't have lock-in, the way those software, and

00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:54.280
that is by design. So we're pleased with this, but it begs the question, again, I said about

00:24:54.280 --> 00:25:01.280
corporations, and are we trustworthy? And I would say we're not at face value trustworthy

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:05.280
because in today's world, corporations, and I'm going to get into this in a little more

00:25:05.280 --> 00:25:10.280
detail in a minute, they are pure profit maximizers. So they're by default, you shouldn't

00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:17.280
trust corporations. I think our community needs more than we're a corporation that has

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:24.280
acted well in the past in order to place their trust in the work that we're doing. And I

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:30.280
think customers need to trust that we're looking for a relationship of mutual benefit and that

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:35.280
we're not going to exploit our position as a software vendor in the future, as has happened

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:40.280
with other proprietary software companies in the past. So we need to build, we need

00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:45.280
to make our motivation as clear and transparent as possible, and we need to try to build more

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:50.280
real long-term trust, and I think some of that has to do with the nature of corporations,

00:25:50.280 --> 00:25:56.280
how corporations work, and how maybe corporations actually need to evolve. So I'm going to go

00:25:56.280 --> 00:26:01.280
back, this is a little bit elemental, but I think it's not something that I had thought

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:06.280
really carefully and critically about until a few years ago. What actually is a corporation?

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:14.280
Why do they even exist? And what a corporation is, is actually, it's a virtual person. So

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:20.280
it's acting as a person, legally a person, but it's actually, it's constituted by a group

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:27.280
of people. So why do we even have corporations? Well, what did we do before corporations?

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:33.280
Before corporations, any business that existed was either undertaken by an individual or

00:26:33.280 --> 00:26:38.280
maybe a partnership of individuals. And so the individuals were actually personally liable

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:42.280
for everything the enterprise did. And when a contract was made between a business and

00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:46.280
another party, it was actually a contract with the individual or the group of individuals.

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:50.280
So when someone left a company, the contracts actually had to be renegotiated. Business

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:55.280
was really fundamentally person to person. And that meant that anything that a business

00:26:55.280 --> 00:27:00.280
could accomplish was sort of bounded by what one person's assets could accomplish and what

00:27:00.280 --> 00:27:08.280
liability one person was willing to accrue. So as the industrial age progressed, this

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:13.280
model sort of didn't seem adequate, and the first corporations were actually formed by

00:27:13.280 --> 00:27:18.280
Royal Act, the East India Company being one of the most significant examples of that.

00:27:18.280 --> 00:27:25.280
And then as governments realized that we needed things like bridges, railways, banks, utilities,

00:27:25.280 --> 00:27:29.280
we need to operate at a different scale than individuals have been able to operate at.

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:36.280
So they created this instrument called a corporation that they believed needed this sort of absolving

00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:41.280
of liability and additional capital that the corporate model provided for.

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:46.280
So if you think about then the essential nature of a corporation, it's an institution that

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:52.280
is actually created by government in order to benefit the societies that govern. That

00:27:52.280 --> 00:27:57.280
was the original purpose of corporations. And this worked very well and served the public

00:27:57.280 --> 00:28:03.280
benefit in many regards. But if you look at that second bullet, you know, about without

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:08.280
fear of personal liability, that actually is a recipe for bad behavior, and we've seen

00:28:08.280 --> 00:28:14.280
that play out as well. So what we have today with corporations has worked well, but I think

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:17.280
we're seeing it crack a little bit in the contemporary world.

00:28:17.280 --> 00:28:22.280
So if you think about the legal theories of what the primary purpose of a corporation

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:28.280
is, there's actually two competing theories. One is stakeholder. This is kind of the original

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:34.280
idea and sort of the original idea that I've been sort of advocating for, which is that

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:38.280
the corporation is created by the government and therefore has a social function. And the

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:42.280
directors and officers of the corporation should consider all the stakeholders affected

00:28:42.280 --> 00:28:47.280
by the corporation, employees, the environment, the community, shareholders, kind of looking

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:50.280
at everybody's interests when they make decisions.

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:57.280
There's another theory, which is shareholder primacy, and it's a pretty raw notion, which

00:28:57.280 --> 00:29:02.280
is the purpose of a corporation is to maximize value for shareholders within the bounds of

00:29:02.280 --> 00:29:11.280
law. Really narrow. And sadly, that is actually the legal theory that has won in Anglo-American

00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:17.280
legal systems. Shareholder primacy is the law that we live under currently.

00:29:17.280 --> 00:29:23.280
And there's been a couple significant cases that establish that, or many cases that have

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:28.280
sort of built that up. A couple of the more significant ones was in 1919. Ford decided

00:29:28.280 --> 00:29:34.280
that they wanted to produce less expensive products and pay their employees more, so

00:29:34.280 --> 00:29:39.280
they stopped paying dividends to shareholders. Again, balancing the needs of all different

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:42.280
constituencies. And the Michigan Supreme Court said, that's not a thing. You're not allowed

00:29:42.280 --> 00:29:47.280
to do that. Your purpose is to create profit for shareholders. Full stop. You can't do

00:29:48.280 --> 00:29:52.280
that. Another case, a little more contemporary,

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:57.280
Revlon was faced with an acquisition proposal that actually the shareholders, it appealed

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:01.280
to the shareholders, it was a good deal for them, but the board felt that it was going

00:30:01.280 --> 00:30:05.280
to not be a good deal for the employees or the bondholders, people who actually held

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:10.280
debt. And so they tried to block the acquisition, and in this case, the Delaware Supreme Court

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:15.280
rejected the idea that they had the duty or even the option to consider the interests

00:30:16.280 --> 00:30:20.280
of stakeholders other than shareholders. So there's been a number of cases like that,

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:27.280
and that's kind of where we stand with corporate law. And many people find this lacking. Companies

00:30:29.280 --> 00:30:34.280
while they're pursuing profit can create lots and lots of public health and environmental

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:40.280
problems. They can create systemic risks, as we saw with recent financial crises. It

00:30:40.280 --> 00:30:45.280
leads back to the question is that we've given these corporations a special legal status.

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:51.280
Does that carry any reciprocal obligation to the public good? And shouldn't companies

00:30:51.280 --> 00:30:55.280
be able to consider the welfare of their own employees in their community when they make

00:30:55.280 --> 00:31:00.280
decisions? A lot of the bad behavior you see by corporations is precisely because they

00:31:00.280 --> 00:31:05.280
can't consider, legally can't consider these things.

00:31:05.280 --> 00:31:11.280
So in response to this, a bunch of states have actually adopted legislation that permit,

00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:16.280
note permit not require, permit directors to consider things other than shareholder

00:31:16.280 --> 00:31:22.280
value. And now we've seen recently this last year, there's this group called the Business

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:28.280
Roundtable that's composed of a bunch of CEOs of mostly big public companies, and for the

00:31:28.280 --> 00:31:33.280
first time since 1997, they in a public statement said that corporations shouldn't exist solely

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:39.280
to serve shareholders. So that's, I think people are sensing that this regime is wrong.

00:31:39.280 --> 00:31:44.280
This isn't really talking about fundamentally changing the system. This is just more saying

00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:50.280
we have dissatisfaction with the system. So what can be done to change the system? So

00:31:50.280 --> 00:31:54.280
I don't know how many of you have heard of the company AND1. Have people heard of AND1?

00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:59.280
It's a basketball shoe company. And I think as it will turn out, this company will be

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:05.280
very significant in the history of corporate law and perhaps of capitalism. So let me tell

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:11.280
you a little bit about AND1. Basketball shoe company founded in 1993. They were a socially

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:16.280
responsible business. They had great, they treated their employees really well, had great

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:23.280
benefits. They allocated 5% of their profits to local charities, and significantly they,

00:32:23.280 --> 00:32:28.280
they're a shoe company so they had overseas factories. They worked to implement a supplier

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:33.280
code of conduct to make sure that workers in overseas factories were treated well, safely,

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:38.280
had good wages, et cetera. So they were sort of a socially responsible business kind of

00:32:38.280 --> 00:32:44.280
before that became something that more widely practiced. So what happened to AND1? Well,

00:32:44.280 --> 00:32:49.280
they were pretty small in the mid-90s. They took on external investors in 1999, and it

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:56.280
turned out that they grew quite a bit over, over that span from 95 to 2001. But then ultimately

00:32:56.280 --> 00:33:01.280
they had competition from Nike and others, and their sales dropped, and they were sort

00:33:01.280 --> 00:33:05.280
of forced to sell the company. And what was really surprising and disturbing to the founders

00:33:05.280 --> 00:33:10.280
was, who created this company with the idea, we created the company, we control the company,

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:15.280
we want to build a socially responsible business. When they went to sell the company, it was

00:33:15.280 --> 00:33:20.280
done exclusively to maximize shareholder value. And so after the sale, and they could do nothing

00:33:20.280 --> 00:33:26.280
about this, all those commitments to employees or overseas workers and local community were

00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:32.280
just stripped away. So they were shocked and disappointed, and it made them think something

00:33:32.280 --> 00:33:39.280
needs to change. So they got together with a friend of theirs to start a nonprofit called

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:44.280
B-Lab, and the idea behind B-Lab was to create a new form of corporate governance. So they

00:33:44.280 --> 00:33:49.280
created the nonprofit, and they actually created a new corporate structure called a

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:55.280
benefit corporation. And this is a reaction to the shareholder primacy regime, where the

00:33:55.280 --> 00:34:01.280
directors of the company are legally required to account for all of the stakeholders, community,

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:06.280
employees, in their decisions. It's a legal requirement, not an option. And they also

00:34:06.280 --> 00:34:10.280
name a public beneficial purpose as part of their charter, that again, they are accountable

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:17.280
to pursue, legally accountable to pursue. I won't read this in detail, but you can see

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:22.280
a little bit of the actual legislation behind Delaware Public Benefit Corporations, and

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:26.280
it puts a stringent legal requirement on the directors to act in a different way, to not

00:34:26.280 --> 00:34:34.280
use the shareholder primacy regime. So this nonprofit has actually been successful in

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:39.280
getting 34 states to pass legislation that permit benefit corporations. There's currently

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:43.280
over 7,000 of them. These are some examples. You've probably heard of some of these, some

00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:47.280
of these companies, and you might not have known that they were a benefit corporation.

00:34:47.280 --> 00:34:53.280
In addition to these companies, there are some public company, so the line at the top

00:34:53.280 --> 00:34:56.280
are public companies. They're not benefit corporations, but they have wholly owned

00:34:56.280 --> 00:35:01.280
subsidiaries that are, in fact, benefit corporations. So I think this benefit corporation

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:06.280
idea has the seeds of what it takes to transform what corporations are and how they relate

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:11.280
to their world and to their communities and all of their stakeholders, and it kind of

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:17.280
takes this idea of good companies that has existed over the last 20 years, whether that

00:35:17.280 --> 00:35:23.280
be about Energy Star compliance or fair trade or organic food, and it elevates that to the

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:28.280
idea of good companies. So most of you or many of you can probably guess what the next

00:35:28.280 --> 00:35:33.280
slide of this presentation is going to be. I'm really happy to announce today that we

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:37.280
are now a certified Delaware benefit corporation.

00:35:52.280 --> 00:35:59.280
So we actually have a new name. We're no longer RStudio Inc. We're RStudio PBC, and we've

00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:04.280
always tried to run the company this way. That's always been what we've tried to do,

00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:09.280
but now it's actually baked into our charter. It's part of our corporate DNA. It's a requirement,

00:36:09.280 --> 00:36:15.280
not something that we do at our discretion. As part of it, we actually name a public benefit,

00:36:15.280 --> 00:36:20.280
and that actually goes into our charter. This is our public benefit, and you note that we

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:25.280
cite the creation of free and open source software for data science, scientific research,

00:36:25.280 --> 00:36:28.280
and technical communication. It's a little bit broader than data science.

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:34.280
Today we're just data science, but I'm optimistic that we have created a model that actually

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:38.280
is a better model for scientific and technical software. So someday I think it would be nice

00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:42.280
to do more within scientific computing. So that's why we wrote the public benefit a little

00:36:42.280 --> 00:36:49.280
bit more broadly. As part of being a public benefit corporation, we actually will release

00:36:49.280 --> 00:36:55.280
an annual report describing kind of how we've served our public beneficial purpose. We posted

00:36:55.280 --> 00:37:01.280
the first of those reports on our website. A few highlights. We provide some metrics

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:05.280
around kind of our investment in open source projects, and I said before there's over 250

00:37:05.280 --> 00:37:10.280
of them. We dedicate over half of the company's engineering resources to open source. Right

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:14.280
now we have 36 full-time engineers that work on open source software, and that's broken

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:18.280
down kind of by project in the report. And there have been hundreds of millions of downloads

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:23.280
of our open source products and packages. So these are metrics we're going to keep reporting

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:29.280
on every year. So in addition to being a benefit corporation, the B Lab has actually

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:33.280
created a certification program that both looks at whether you've changed your charter,

00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:38.280
but also looks at your impact specifically on your workers, customers, community, and

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:43.280
environment, and actually rates you across a bunch of categories. So we're happy to also

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:48.280
share that we've been certified as a B Corp by the B Lab, and you can see our impact report

00:37:48.280 --> 00:37:55.280
there, which actually has all those ratings, is also available now.

00:37:55.280 --> 00:38:00.280
Some of this, though, begs the question. We've become a B Corp, and that reflects, I think,

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:06.280
who we are and what we're about and what we aim to be, but it also doesn't necessarily

00:38:06.280 --> 00:38:11.280
talk about the future. And I want to tell everyone here that our plan is to remain an

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:18.280
independent company, to never sell the company. But, you know, yes. So that is what we're

00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:24.280
going to do. But how can we actually make that happen? How can we provide assurance

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:29.280
that that's going to happen? We do have outside investors as minority shareholders, and prior

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:34.280
to this conversion, we actually had written into the financing documents, I had special

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:40.280
rights that I could block what I say, undesirable outcomes. I could individually block the sale

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:46.280
of the company. But, you know, just saying that I can block the sale of the company

00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:51.280
isn't really fully reassuring, because, you know, what if I die? What if I change my mind?

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:55.280
So it's a little over-reliant on one individual, so we also, along with the transition, made

00:38:55.280 --> 00:39:00.280
some changes to kind of how those shares are held and how the rights are exercised. So

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:05.280
now there's actually a group of people all inside the company who exercise those rights.

00:39:05.280 --> 00:39:11.280
So if I, you know, die or change my mind or anything like that, we still have those

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:20.280
protections in place. And before I conclude, I wanted to also talk about kind of who ultimately

00:39:20.280 --> 00:39:25.280
benefits from RStudio's success. As I said in the talk, we've tried to build a company

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:30.280
where we have lots of beneficiaries. All of our stakeholders are beneficiaries. We do

00:39:31.280 --> 00:39:36.280
have shareholders, and the traditional way that shareholders get remunerated is usually

00:39:36.280 --> 00:39:41.280
either selling the company or going public. So that is not our plan. So what we're going

00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:44.280
to do is take our profits and use those to purchase stock back from our shareholders

00:39:44.280 --> 00:39:50.280
over time. So once we've met that commitment, we are going to dedicate a substantial portion

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:57.280
of our profits to philanthropic causes that relate to our mission of open source software

00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:02.280
and open science. And those donations, we've documented in this year's annual report the

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:08.280
donations that we've made. But as we are able to purchase stock back from our shareholders

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:11.280
and dedicate more of our profits to these donations, we'll also report specifically

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:17.280
on that in our annual public benefit report. So thank you all very much for helping us

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:23.280
to build this company and build this community. It's been an incredible experience, far exceeding

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:28.280
anything I could have ever hoped for, and I'm excited for what the future holds. Thank you.

00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:56.280
Thank you.

